And we'll take your questions
as we get towards the end of

00:02:44.810 --> 00:02:45.930
the session.

00:02:45.930 --> 00:02:49.970
So with that, I want to take it
over to Nicole to start and

00:02:49.970 --> 00:02:53.870
say, Nicole, when you started
thinking about this project,

00:02:53.870 --> 00:02:59.650
where did your initial
inspiration

00:02:59.650 --> 00:03:02.540
come from for this?

00:03:02.540 --> 00:03:07.230
NICOLE MCDONALD: Well, we
actually really researched

00:03:07.230 --> 00:03:13.410
Cirque du Soleil, and the
brand, and also the live

00:03:13.410 --> 00:03:17.840
shows, and we tried to figure
out where to bring the live

00:03:17.840 --> 00:03:19.530
show into an interactive
space.

00:03:19.530 --> 00:03:23.450
And one of the inspirations
was magic.

00:03:23.450 --> 00:03:29.930
Magic is something that draws us
in, [INAUDIBLE] to the eye.

00:03:29.930 --> 00:03:32.210
It's visceral.

00:03:32.210 --> 00:03:35.880
There's emotion behind it, and
that's where we, kind of-- we

00:03:35.880 --> 00:03:37.130
thought about magic.

00:03:39.920 --> 00:03:42.470
Magic [INAUDIBLE].

00:03:42.470 --> 00:03:45.100
PETE LEPAGE: So what about the
magic of Cirque du Soleil sort

00:03:45.100 --> 00:03:48.340
of brought you to
that experience?

00:03:48.340 --> 00:03:51.780
What were some of the things
that you thought about that

00:03:51.780 --> 00:03:54.776
would translate well
to the web?

00:03:54.776 --> 00:03:57.513
NICOLE MCDONALD: Well, one of
the things that I think Cirque

00:03:57.513 --> 00:04:02.140
du Soleil does extremely,
extremely well is, it kind of

00:04:02.140 --> 00:04:04.750
is a feast of sense.

00:04:04.750 --> 00:04:07.630
It's so beautiful, there's so
many colors, there's so many

00:04:07.630 --> 00:04:08.770
things going on.

00:04:08.770 --> 00:04:11.900
It's just hyper,
hyper gorgeous.

00:04:11.900 --> 00:04:13.300
[INAUDIBLE]

00:04:13.300 --> 00:04:16.720
points, well, one of the points
that we wanted to be

00:04:16.720 --> 00:04:22.340
careful of was that in a live
experience, we feel connected

00:04:22.340 --> 00:04:25.630
in ways that we don't when
we sit behind a computer.

00:04:25.630 --> 00:04:31.895
And so one of our wants was to
really figure out how we could

00:04:31.895 --> 00:04:38.820
get closer to the action and
experience it, maybe, in that

00:04:38.820 --> 00:04:40.670
same way we would with
a live event.

00:04:40.670 --> 00:04:41.910
PETE LEPAGE: Cool.

00:04:41.910 --> 00:04:45.030
And Gillian, for you, as you
started to look at this

00:04:45.030 --> 00:04:47.470
project and start thinking about
this project, where did

00:04:47.470 --> 00:04:48.880
the inspiration come
from for you?

00:04:51.500 --> 00:04:54.210
GILLIAN FERRABEE: I think for
us, the first meetings we had,

00:04:54.210 --> 00:04:56.840
the two things that came up as
themes in terms of bringing

00:04:56.840 --> 00:05:03.230
Cirque du Soleil to the world
of the web was curiosity is

00:05:03.230 --> 00:05:05.110
something that Cirque
creates for their

00:05:05.110 --> 00:05:06.890
audience as a way to engage.

00:05:06.890 --> 00:05:09.540
So as Nicole said, it's magical,
and you want to

00:05:09.540 --> 00:05:12.723
understand what's behind that
magic or where that magic is

00:05:12.723 --> 00:05:14.530
going to take you.

00:05:14.530 --> 00:05:19.080
So that idea of still being
able stretch people's

00:05:19.080 --> 00:05:23.195
imagination and initiate
curiosity, which would give

00:05:23.195 --> 00:05:25.970
someone the desire, then, to
move forward and into the

00:05:25.970 --> 00:05:29.180
experience, in the sense
of interactivity.

00:05:29.180 --> 00:05:32.285
And the other thing that came
up for us is adventure.

00:05:32.285 --> 00:05:34.650
Because the web gives this sense
that you can access the

00:05:34.650 --> 00:05:37.180
whole world.

00:05:37.180 --> 00:05:38.520
What's the edge of the map?

00:05:38.520 --> 00:05:39.740
How far can you go?

00:05:39.740 --> 00:05:41.850
And how wide can you reach?

00:05:41.850 --> 00:05:45.210
So [INAUDIBLE] came up with
curiosity, in the sense of

00:05:45.210 --> 00:05:46.670
magic, and adventure.

00:05:46.670 --> 00:05:50.580
PETE LEPAGE: Cool I think, for
me, one of the really amazing

00:05:50.580 --> 00:05:54.010
things about the web
is that we are

00:05:54.010 --> 00:05:55.180
always pushing it forward.

00:05:55.180 --> 00:05:56.670
Or we're always trying
to push it forward.

00:05:56.670 --> 00:06:00.310
And that's certainly one of the
main components of Chrome

00:06:00.310 --> 00:06:04.390
experiments is, like, we can
take the web here, and what we

00:06:04.390 --> 00:06:06.770
do to push it to that
really neat thing?

00:06:06.770 --> 00:06:10.710
And how do we make it do
something it's never seen

00:06:10.710 --> 00:06:13.760
somebody do before?

00:06:13.760 --> 00:06:17.700
Nicole, when you started working
on this, how did the

00:06:17.700 --> 00:06:23.120
technology affect your
inspiration?

00:06:23.120 --> 00:06:25.485
NICOLE MCDONALD: Well, it's
actually going back to the

00:06:25.485 --> 00:06:28.660
live shows.

00:06:28.660 --> 00:06:31.730
Even though you're not
necessarily interacting, it is

00:06:31.730 --> 00:06:33.740
still a 3D experience.

00:06:33.740 --> 00:06:38.440
And one of the things that I
really wanted was to have it

00:06:38.440 --> 00:06:41.530
be engaging in a
3D experience.

00:06:41.530 --> 00:06:45.970
And so that's where we came up
with the idea that we were

00:06:45.970 --> 00:06:49.440
using a 2D world
in a 3D space.

00:06:49.440 --> 00:06:54.890
And so I think the technology
allowed us to really create a

00:06:54.890 --> 00:06:58.360
layered environment.

00:06:58.360 --> 00:07:01.890
And that, I think, started to
snowball into, how do you

00:07:01.890 --> 00:07:04.520
create a layered environment?

00:07:04.520 --> 00:07:05.040
What does it do?

00:07:05.040 --> 00:07:06.210
How does it react?

00:07:06.210 --> 00:07:06.680
Why does react?

00:07:06.680 --> 00:07:11.400
And I think that's a good
question is, why?

00:07:11.400 --> 00:07:12.386
Why use technology?

00:07:12.386 --> 00:07:16.560
And it's really to tell
more of a story.

00:07:16.560 --> 00:07:19.900
PETE LEPAGE: So you see
technology being a good way to

00:07:19.900 --> 00:07:24.950
tell a better story and engage
with people in storytelling

00:07:24.950 --> 00:07:28.185
and more dynamic experiences?

00:07:28.185 --> 00:07:30.330
NICOLE MCDONALD: Yeah, from
an artistic level, I think

00:07:30.330 --> 00:07:32.870
technology is a paintbrush,
right?

00:07:32.870 --> 00:07:34.330
So it's in size.

00:07:34.330 --> 00:07:36.662
You can either use a fat
one, or you use a

00:07:36.662 --> 00:07:38.270
smaller one for details.

00:07:38.270 --> 00:07:42.880
I think that technology is
also just a way-- it's an

00:07:42.880 --> 00:07:44.920
outlet to communicate ideas.

00:07:44.920 --> 00:07:48.260
And the exciting thing about
it is, like you said, it's

00:07:48.260 --> 00:07:49.410
never been done before.

00:07:49.410 --> 00:07:52.066
But also, we can pull in people
to dream in ways that

00:07:52.066 --> 00:07:53.960
they haven't before.

00:07:53.960 --> 00:07:54.920
PETE LEPAGE: Yeah.

00:07:54.920 --> 00:07:57.010
This is a question for
both of you guys.

00:08:00.440 --> 00:08:04.770
Before you came to the web, or
before you started playing

00:08:04.770 --> 00:08:11.680
with technology, what is your
creative experiences based on?

00:08:11.680 --> 00:08:15.590
Did it come from painting,
drawing, or did it always

00:08:15.590 --> 00:08:17.730
really exist around the web?

00:08:20.251 --> 00:08:20.850
NICOLE MCDONALD: Gillian?

00:08:20.850 --> 00:08:22.330
[LAUGHS].

00:08:22.330 --> 00:08:23.906
GILLIAN FERRABEE: Wow.

00:08:23.906 --> 00:08:26.110
Well, my personal history
goes way back.

00:08:26.110 --> 00:08:30.740
I've been performing and making
art since as long as I

00:08:30.740 --> 00:08:30.810
can remember.

00:08:30.810 --> 00:08:36.380
My mother's a designer and an
artist and an educator.

00:08:36.380 --> 00:08:40.650
But for me, it's been
mostly live and some

00:08:40.650 --> 00:08:42.655
drawing, music, singing.

00:08:42.655 --> 00:08:47.480
But the primary has been live
audience, traditional and

00:08:47.480 --> 00:08:48.990
nontraditional stage.

00:08:48.990 --> 00:08:51.700
PETE LEPAGE: OK

00:08:51.700 --> 00:08:56.640
NICOLE MCDONALD: And for me,
my background has been

00:08:56.640 --> 00:08:57.430
everything.

00:08:57.430 --> 00:08:59.685
You know, wit Christmas every
year, I got a new art kit.

00:09:04.090 --> 00:09:05.800
I was constantly a
little artist.

00:09:05.800 --> 00:09:10.020
I started, actually, in college
as a performance and

00:09:10.020 --> 00:09:11.770
filmmaking and painting.

00:09:11.770 --> 00:09:13.020
[LAUGHS].

00:09:15.010 --> 00:09:18.890
And then I immediately, after
college, went into games.

00:09:18.890 --> 00:09:21.830
And I painted sets for games.

00:09:21.830 --> 00:09:25.190
And that started my interest
in interactive.

00:09:25.190 --> 00:09:27.490
And so I took this fine
art world and

00:09:27.490 --> 00:09:28.900
started making it digital.

00:09:28.900 --> 00:09:32.300
I was really quite lucky.

00:09:32.300 --> 00:09:34.730
PETE LEPAGE: Cool.

00:09:34.730 --> 00:09:39.100
Gillian, when Nicole and the
crew first sat down with you

00:09:39.100 --> 00:09:43.870
guys and said, hey, here's this
really cool experience

00:09:43.870 --> 00:09:46.850
that we're thinking about doing,
and showed some of

00:09:46.850 --> 00:09:49.310
their inspiration and mood
boards, what did you think of

00:09:49.310 --> 00:09:52.050
what they were showing and where
they were going with

00:09:52.050 --> 00:09:55.460
some of these things?

00:09:55.460 --> 00:09:57.780
GILLIAN FERRABEE: Well, the
first thing that was, I think,

00:09:57.780 --> 00:10:00.550
exceptional and almost magical,
really, to use the

00:10:00.550 --> 00:10:04.720
word, was that we had prepared
a mood board, and there was

00:10:04.720 --> 00:10:07.370
actually one image that we both
had chosen for our mood

00:10:07.370 --> 00:10:10.330
board, of all that's possible
to find on the net.

00:10:10.330 --> 00:10:12.900
So that was kind of
mind blowing.

00:10:12.900 --> 00:10:15.230
When they presented their mood
board, we looked at each

00:10:15.230 --> 00:10:18.150
other, like, we didn't give
that to them, did we?

00:10:18.150 --> 00:10:19.730
No, we haven't talked
to each other.

00:10:19.730 --> 00:10:24.970
So there was an immediate
complicity and common vision

00:10:24.970 --> 00:10:28.190
that was obvious from that and
from a few other things.

00:10:28.190 --> 00:10:31.580
And the other thing, from the
Cirque's point of view, that

00:10:31.580 --> 00:10:34.910
was a strong indicator was--

00:10:34.910 --> 00:10:37.200
I can't remember, I think was
Nicole, but somebody brought

00:10:37.200 --> 00:10:41.460
up the idea of the screen, what
you might call the fourth

00:10:41.460 --> 00:10:46.325
wall, and how to playfully
interact with your audience.

00:10:46.325 --> 00:10:48.400
Like now, even, this is live,
we're talking-- how do you

00:10:48.400 --> 00:10:52.730
interact through this new
form of communicator?

00:10:52.730 --> 00:10:54.880
And that was something we were
definitely curious about.

00:10:54.880 --> 00:10:58.660
So those were the two things
that pretty much nailed it.

00:10:58.660 --> 00:10:59.443
PETE LEPAGE: Cool.

00:10:59.443 --> 00:11:02.570
Nicole, what were your feelings
on those first couple

00:11:02.570 --> 00:11:05.130
of meetings, when you sat down
and said, this is what we're

00:11:05.130 --> 00:11:10.060
thinking, going from a really
web and creative background to

00:11:10.060 --> 00:11:13.985
a company who's all
about doing live,

00:11:13.985 --> 00:11:16.950
in-person kind of stuff?

00:11:16.950 --> 00:11:19.720
NICOLE MCDONALD: It was super,
super exciting, obviously, I

00:11:19.720 --> 00:11:22.610
mean, I kind of a dream
come true, really.

00:11:22.610 --> 00:11:28.570
To work with such a creative,
imaginative, really

00:11:28.570 --> 00:11:33.830
responsible company, that's
kind of rare.

00:11:33.830 --> 00:11:41.200
But I think the challenge of
it all was thrilling, to

00:11:41.200 --> 00:11:44.930
really kind of crack open the
nut a little bit and be able

00:11:44.930 --> 00:11:48.185
to do take a step into a
direction of interactive

00:11:48.185 --> 00:11:52.990
performing is super exciting.

00:11:52.990 --> 00:11:55.710
PETE LEPAGE: So as you started
working on some of this stuff

00:11:55.710 --> 00:11:59.470
and sort of took the technology
with your vision,

00:11:59.470 --> 00:12:03.750
how did the technology change
the way that you saw the

00:12:03.750 --> 00:12:10.500
vision being done as you were
working through the project?

00:12:10.500 --> 00:12:13.828
NICOLE MCDONALD: Well, I think
I'm a developer's worst

00:12:13.828 --> 00:12:19.165
nightmare in that [INAUDIBLE],
because I think I know enough

00:12:19.165 --> 00:12:24.790
of what technology can do, I
know where we can push it.

00:12:24.790 --> 00:12:28.550
I think that one of the
challenges for us, from a

00:12:28.550 --> 00:12:31.850
development standpoint was,
could we get things in time?

00:12:31.850 --> 00:12:38.110
Could different technologies be
available at that moment?

00:12:38.110 --> 00:12:42.990
I think that was our
biggest challenge.

00:12:42.990 --> 00:12:46.680
PETE LEPAGE: So whether and
when technology came on,

00:12:46.680 --> 00:12:49.384
whether you had access to it?

00:12:49.384 --> 00:12:52.090
NICOLE MCDONALD: Yeah, and I
think that usually the process

00:12:52.090 --> 00:12:55.630
of how I work in an interactive
space is, we

00:12:55.630 --> 00:12:58.840
dream, and then we kind
of dial it back.

00:12:58.840 --> 00:13:03.570
And then we become detectives
and solve problems, which is,

00:13:03.570 --> 00:13:06.380
I think, the best-case
scenario.

00:13:06.380 --> 00:13:11.283
Solving problems means we move
forward, which is [INAUDIBLE].

00:13:11.283 --> 00:13:14.460
PETE LEPAGE: Were there any
problems that you were really

00:13:14.460 --> 00:13:17.640
proud of having solved with this
project, technology-wise,

00:13:17.640 --> 00:13:19.880
creativity-wise?

00:13:19.880 --> 00:13:21.670
NICOLE MCDONALD: That's a
really good question.

00:13:21.670 --> 00:13:24.643
I think you'll notice that
there's an incredible amount

00:13:24.643 --> 00:13:35.420
of layered sprites and divs,
figuring out what a system

00:13:35.420 --> 00:13:37.280
could handle.

00:13:37.280 --> 00:13:40.760
And you dream big and so you
have, like, seven videos

00:13:40.760 --> 00:13:43.520
playing, and all these
animations, and then there are

00:13:43.520 --> 00:13:45.610
all these huge files.

00:13:45.610 --> 00:13:48.850
And then really figuring
out, OK, now we have--

00:13:48.850 --> 00:13:50.858
it's not moving on a computer.

00:13:50.858 --> 00:13:52.550
So nobody can watch it.

00:13:52.550 --> 00:13:55.620
It looks great, but
nobody can see it.

00:13:55.620 --> 00:13:58.360
Really figuring out what
that wait was.

00:13:58.360 --> 00:14:01.765
So how do we turn this down, but
still, how do we maintain

00:14:01.765 --> 00:14:03.950
our vision?

00:14:03.950 --> 00:14:05.405
PETE LEPAGE: Cool.

00:14:05.405 --> 00:14:06.390
NICOLE MCDONALD: That was
definitely a big challenge.

00:14:06.390 --> 00:14:07.640
PETE LEPAGE: Yeah.

00:14:10.290 --> 00:14:14.980
What was it like going through
the process of saying, OK, so

00:14:14.980 --> 00:14:16.200
we've got our idea here.

00:14:16.200 --> 00:14:18.720
What did the workflow look like,
to say, all right, so

00:14:18.720 --> 00:14:22.310
here's our idea, after those
first meetings with Cirque, to

00:14:22.310 --> 00:14:26.132
then go and get to that
final project?

00:14:26.132 --> 00:14:30.000
NICOLE MCDONALD: Well, we took
some time and wrote the story.

00:14:30.000 --> 00:14:34.240
That was super fun, just
to tell the narrative.

00:14:34.240 --> 00:14:36.570
And then once we had the
narrative, we actually made it

00:14:36.570 --> 00:14:42.025
a functioning animatic And then
from the animatic, it

00:14:42.025 --> 00:14:48.100
kind of gave us the answer of
flow and also an asset list,

00:14:48.100 --> 00:14:51.390
which was super important.

00:14:51.390 --> 00:14:54.410
PETE LEPAGE: For each of the
different scenes, yeah.

00:14:54.410 --> 00:14:55.670
NICOLE MCDONALD: And
then we shot it.

00:14:55.670 --> 00:15:01.280
And then at the shoot, we were
able to kind of pull in video

00:15:01.280 --> 00:15:05.527
live and be able to see how it
moved and whether or not our

00:15:05.527 --> 00:15:08.740
horizon line was correct, or
overshooting it, or even just

00:15:08.740 --> 00:15:11.020
if it was a worthwhile
experience.

00:15:11.020 --> 00:15:16.050
And then from there on,
it was just, go.

00:15:16.050 --> 00:15:19.560
PETE LEPAGE: And Gillian, how
did you see, and how did your

00:15:19.560 --> 00:15:24.140
team work with Nicole to really
take that vision from

00:15:24.140 --> 00:15:25.390
beginning to end?

00:15:29.890 --> 00:15:31.154
GILLIAN FERRABEE: I think the
main thing was keeping in

00:15:31.154 --> 00:15:36.000
touch all along the way so that
everybody had a sense of

00:15:36.000 --> 00:15:38.150
what was happening, what
it looked like.

00:15:38.150 --> 00:15:41.120
Did it match what we wanted
and imagined?

00:15:44.040 --> 00:15:46.620
I can't think of any specific
obstacle, but I know that we

00:15:46.620 --> 00:15:47.380
hit a bunch.

00:15:47.380 --> 00:15:49.950
And Nicole probably
remembers this.

00:15:49.950 --> 00:15:52.810
We would always say, well,
that's because something else

00:15:52.810 --> 00:15:55.970
even better's going to
show up, which it

00:15:55.970 --> 00:15:58.350
actually did, often.

00:15:58.350 --> 00:16:00.850
The part that was most
interesting, for us, I would

00:16:00.850 --> 00:16:05.430
say, was the actual shoot and
watching how the artists,

00:16:05.430 --> 00:16:11.990
themselves, how Nicole was able
to translate to them what

00:16:11.990 --> 00:16:14.400
their work was going to look
like in the final product.

00:16:14.400 --> 00:16:17.200
Because a live performer knows,
they're onstage when

00:16:17.200 --> 00:16:19.370
it's happening.

00:16:19.370 --> 00:16:21.330
So what they give comes
from that knowledge.

00:16:21.330 --> 00:16:24.870
And so Nicole was able to inform
them the context that

00:16:24.870 --> 00:16:27.980
they were performing in, what
it would look like, and then

00:16:27.980 --> 00:16:30.610
they were able to play and adapt
with that, which was

00:16:30.610 --> 00:16:31.900
exciting for us to see that.

00:16:31.900 --> 00:16:34.760
NICOLE MCDONALD: Yeah, and
I think that's where the

00:16:34.760 --> 00:16:39.270
animatic played an incredible
role, and also being able to

00:16:39.270 --> 00:16:41.760
input stuff immediately live.

00:16:41.760 --> 00:16:45.060
In a green screen environment,
it's cold.

00:16:45.060 --> 00:16:47.980
There's no connection.

00:16:47.980 --> 00:16:52.720
And I think that was super
exciting that we were able to

00:16:52.720 --> 00:16:57.085
show the artists where they were
in the space and really

00:16:57.085 --> 00:17:01.272
let them have that world and
take over that world.

00:17:01.272 --> 00:17:06.480
PETE LEPAGE: Yeah, actually, I
just got some of the green

00:17:06.480 --> 00:17:10.670
screen video set up so that we
can see have a quick peek at

00:17:10.670 --> 00:17:11.599
that, I think.

00:17:11.599 --> 00:17:14.700
Let me see if I can get
that running here.

00:17:14.700 --> 00:17:15.450
There we go.

00:17:15.450 --> 00:17:18.210
So we've got some picture in
picture going so that folks

00:17:18.210 --> 00:17:19.900
can see what's going on there.

00:17:19.900 --> 00:17:25.089
So this was the scene where
our guide jumps

00:17:25.089 --> 00:17:27.569
backwards off the log.

00:17:27.569 --> 00:17:32.350
And you can see her there
on that blue screen.

00:17:32.350 --> 00:17:34.840
Nicole, as we run through that,
what was your process of

00:17:34.840 --> 00:17:38.460
thinking through how to do these
things, because you see

00:17:38.460 --> 00:17:39.890
just this blue screen.

00:17:39.890 --> 00:17:44.470
And the artist has really no
idea, we have really no idea,

00:17:44.470 --> 00:17:49.755
until we see what's going
on, what to expect.

00:17:49.755 --> 00:17:51.340
NICOLE MCDONALD: Well, what we
tried to do is to have some

00:17:51.340 --> 00:17:56.270
key frames to show the artist
where they were in the space,

00:17:56.270 --> 00:18:00.630
and also for us to be able
to plan appropriately.

00:18:00.630 --> 00:18:03.790
This is an A-camera.

00:18:03.790 --> 00:18:08.320
We don't have a B-camera to cut
to, so the entire scene is

00:18:08.320 --> 00:18:10.100
first person POV.

00:18:10.100 --> 00:18:14.710
So we really needed to make sure
that there was a thread

00:18:14.710 --> 00:18:17.655
throughout-- like a breadcrumb
trail continuous, throughout

00:18:17.655 --> 00:18:19.260
the experience.

00:18:19.260 --> 00:18:25.220
And with these frames, we were
also able to build out the 3D

00:18:25.220 --> 00:18:30.720
experience, and then immediately
key the video and

00:18:30.720 --> 00:18:34.370
put them into an environment
to help the artist see what

00:18:34.370 --> 00:18:37.220
space they were working
in, and to--

00:18:41.050 --> 00:18:44.220
what was the first film of Star
Wars that came out, where

00:18:44.220 --> 00:18:46.240
they used blue screen
everywhere?

00:18:49.810 --> 00:18:52.020
PETE LEPAGE: The remakes,
or the--

00:18:52.020 --> 00:18:52.586
NICOLE MCDONALD: The new ones.

00:18:52.586 --> 00:18:53.400
PETE LEPAGE: Oh, yes.

00:18:53.400 --> 00:18:56.150
NICOLE MCDONALD: I just remember
how cold that was.

00:18:56.150 --> 00:18:57.770
There was no connection.

00:18:57.770 --> 00:18:59.980
And there was just
these two people

00:18:59.980 --> 00:19:01.230
speaking to one another.

00:19:04.480 --> 00:19:06.480
We were joking and saying, we
do not want to create that.

00:19:09.040 --> 00:19:13.250
PETE LEPAGE: Gillian, for you
guys, was this the first big

00:19:13.250 --> 00:19:15.810
web project that you guys had
worked on at Cirque du Soleil?

00:19:15.810 --> 00:19:18.685
Or how had you guys worked
with the web before?

00:19:21.380 --> 00:19:22.280
GILLIAN FERRABEE: It was
the first creative

00:19:22.280 --> 00:19:23.630
project, I would say.

00:19:23.630 --> 00:19:27.880
Obviously Cirque has done lots
of marketing, and the company

00:19:27.880 --> 00:19:32.385
website, and other, more
traditional, transitions to

00:19:32.385 --> 00:19:34.860
the web, doing things that
people were doing anyway,

00:19:34.860 --> 00:19:36.130
before the web, but in
a different way.

00:19:36.130 --> 00:19:38.360
But this was the actual--

00:19:38.360 --> 00:19:41.175
the content was created
for this project, and

00:19:41.175 --> 00:19:42.690
it was fully creative.

00:19:42.690 --> 00:19:45.160
[INAUDIBLE].

00:19:45.160 --> 00:19:47.950
PETE LEPAGE: Were you somewhat
skeptical at the beginning, or

00:19:47.950 --> 00:19:51.700
did you think that we would
be able to create such an

00:19:51.700 --> 00:19:58.040
immersive, Cirque-like
experience right off the bat?

00:19:58.040 --> 00:20:00.942
GILLIAN FERRABEE: I'm a highly
optimistic person, so I wasn't

00:20:00.942 --> 00:20:03.407
skeptical, because I
almost never am.

00:20:03.407 --> 00:20:05.790
But I would say there
were definitely lots

00:20:05.790 --> 00:20:08.970
of people who were.

00:20:08.970 --> 00:20:12.180
And the minute we met Nicole and
their team, that went out

00:20:12.180 --> 00:20:12.860
the window.

00:20:12.860 --> 00:20:13.860
Their enthusiasm--

00:20:13.860 --> 00:20:19.750
and maybe they were as highly
optimistic, but they were the

00:20:19.750 --> 00:20:21.180
experts, and they seemed really

00:20:21.180 --> 00:20:23.080
excited that it was possible.

00:20:23.080 --> 00:20:26.320
So that schooled us
pretty quickly.

00:20:26.320 --> 00:20:27.570
PETE LEPAGE: That's
awesome, yeah.

00:20:30.200 --> 00:20:32.540
How would you describe the
difference between working

00:20:32.540 --> 00:20:36.980
with a web experience and
working with a live show,

00:20:36.980 --> 00:20:40.304
starting something like that?

00:20:40.304 --> 00:20:42.400
GILLIAN FERRABEE: Wow, that's
a good question.

00:20:42.400 --> 00:20:46.650
It's completely different,
because, from the beginning,

00:20:46.650 --> 00:20:49.120
your framework is
not a theater.

00:20:49.120 --> 00:20:52.070
It's not an audience.

00:20:52.070 --> 00:20:53.810
It's a platform, in a way.

00:20:53.810 --> 00:20:54.480
It's a tool.

00:20:54.480 --> 00:21:00.410
But there's much more unknown,
which can be exciting, except

00:21:00.410 --> 00:21:03.540
that, when you're doing a show,
the parameters are very

00:21:03.540 --> 00:21:05.080
concrete and practical.

00:21:05.080 --> 00:21:07.760
PETE LEPAGE: Right.

00:21:07.760 --> 00:21:08.940
GILLIAN FERRABEE:
Go ahead Nicole?

00:21:08.940 --> 00:21:10.090
NICOLE MCDONALD: I was just
going to say, I think it's

00:21:10.090 --> 00:21:13.336
practical because it's known.

00:21:13.336 --> 00:21:16.951
Because we haven't defined the
process of interactive--

00:21:16.951 --> 00:21:20.460
there is no cookie cutter
process, necessarily.

00:21:20.460 --> 00:21:27.900
I think that that's the exciting
and the scary part.

00:21:27.900 --> 00:21:28.580
GILLIAN FERRABEE:
It's definitely

00:21:28.580 --> 00:21:29.415
exciting for Cirque.

00:21:29.415 --> 00:21:32.120
And the first question we asked
ourselves is, what are

00:21:32.120 --> 00:21:35.530
all the things that we can't do
in a live show because of

00:21:35.530 --> 00:21:40.660
the parameters of time, or the
weight of something, or the

00:21:40.660 --> 00:21:43.340
feasibility, visually?

00:21:43.340 --> 00:21:46.890
The suspension of disbelief is
completely different live.

00:21:46.890 --> 00:21:50.865
So it's a very exciting
terrain.

00:21:54.260 --> 00:21:58.090
I mean, Cirque has always been
interested in the unknown, as

00:21:58.090 --> 00:21:59.340
Nicole said.

00:21:59.340 --> 00:22:01.530
PETE LEPAGE: So what were some
of the things that, right off

00:22:01.530 --> 00:22:04.160
the bat, when you said, what are
the things we can't do a

00:22:04.160 --> 00:22:06.220
live show, what were some of the
things that you said, we

00:22:06.220 --> 00:22:08.510
can't do, could we do
these on the web?

00:22:11.650 --> 00:22:16.730
GILLIAN FERRABEE: The first
thing that comes up is, in the

00:22:16.730 --> 00:22:21.170
web, you have, to some
degree more say how

00:22:21.170 --> 00:22:22.030
the story is told.

00:22:22.030 --> 00:22:23.700
Because live, you don't
know where the

00:22:23.700 --> 00:22:25.980
person's going to look.

00:22:25.980 --> 00:22:29.040
Which Cirque is a real master
of giving people lots of

00:22:29.040 --> 00:22:32.490
things to look at and, in a way,
guiding their attention.

00:22:35.000 --> 00:22:36.170
So that's different.

00:22:36.170 --> 00:22:39.750
On the web, it gives more
of a traditional

00:22:39.750 --> 00:22:42.240
storytelling process.

00:22:42.240 --> 00:22:46.690
And the other thing
is practical--

00:22:46.690 --> 00:22:49.580
like, to get something onto
stage takes time.

00:22:49.580 --> 00:22:51.650
And to get it off takes time.

00:22:51.650 --> 00:22:54.690
And when you're shooting, you
can do that before you turn

00:22:54.690 --> 00:22:57.560
the camera on for however
long it takes.

00:22:57.560 --> 00:23:03.540
So that's a very practical and
very creative examples.

00:23:03.540 --> 00:23:06.950
PETE LEPAGE: Were there any
things in the Movi.Kanti.Revo

00:23:06.950 --> 00:23:11.760
experience that you pushed
to have them try

00:23:11.760 --> 00:23:13.010
some of those things?

00:23:17.720 --> 00:23:19.682
GILLIAN FERRABEE: Nothing
comes to mind because my

00:23:19.682 --> 00:23:22.530
experience is that Nicole
and [INAUDIBLE]

00:23:22.530 --> 00:23:24.710
surprised us over and over.

00:23:24.710 --> 00:23:26.270
We didn't have time
to catch up.

00:23:28.990 --> 00:23:30.970
NICOLE MCDONALD: From our
perspective, I think it was

00:23:30.970 --> 00:23:35.650
about, really, how to challenge
this experience of

00:23:35.650 --> 00:23:39.940
intimate, a one-on-one
experience, whereas in the

00:23:39.940 --> 00:23:43.260
theater, there's many, many
people around you.

00:23:43.260 --> 00:23:46.740
So how do I engage somebody in
the one-on-one experience?

00:23:46.740 --> 00:23:48.890
And then also perspective--

00:23:48.890 --> 00:23:53.990
we can gauge perspective
behind a computer.

00:23:53.990 --> 00:23:56.580
In a theater, you're
in a seat.

00:23:56.580 --> 00:23:57.220
[INAUDIBLE]

00:23:57.220 --> 00:24:01.140
that Cirque does an amazing
job doing many shows, like

00:24:01.140 --> 00:24:05.040
you're moving around the space
as much as they're moving

00:24:05.040 --> 00:24:06.430
around you.

00:24:06.430 --> 00:24:08.200
But I think that's a really
super interesting thing for

00:24:08.200 --> 00:24:12.570
how to translate live experience
in the future is,

00:24:12.570 --> 00:24:15.750
it's a virtual theater seat.

00:24:15.750 --> 00:24:19.200
PETE LEPAGE: Yeah actually,
that's a perfect segue into

00:24:19.200 --> 00:24:22.263
the next question I have, which
is, what do you think

00:24:22.263 --> 00:24:26.240
that the web brings to
experiences that you can't do

00:24:26.240 --> 00:24:29.960
in a live show?

00:24:29.960 --> 00:24:34.030
And where do you see that going
and changing the way

00:24:34.030 --> 00:24:40.840
some, not just Cirque shows, but
in all live entertainment

00:24:40.840 --> 00:24:43.668
changes in the future?

00:24:43.668 --> 00:24:46.530
NICOLE MCDONALD: That's
a very good--

00:24:46.530 --> 00:24:51.370
I mean, I don't really think we
know quite yet until we do.

00:24:51.370 --> 00:24:55.900
Because I think the wonderful
part of about doing stories

00:24:55.900 --> 00:24:58.480
interactively is that every
single time, we find out

00:24:58.480 --> 00:25:02.650
something new about a way to
engage somebody differently.

00:25:02.650 --> 00:25:08.650
And that's, I think, the part
of the process that is the

00:25:08.650 --> 00:25:11.280
most challenging, because
it's almost like--

00:25:11.280 --> 00:25:13.980
and I think this is why my
developers kind of hate me

00:25:13.980 --> 00:25:17.480
sometimes-- not hate me,
but obviously, raise

00:25:17.480 --> 00:25:19.560
their fist to me--

00:25:19.560 --> 00:25:22.870
is because I think I'm
constantly using technology in

00:25:22.870 --> 00:25:25.080
ways that it's not supposed
to be used.

00:25:25.080 --> 00:25:27.190
And that's how we
move forward.

00:25:27.190 --> 00:25:30.790
That's how we push the lines.

00:25:30.790 --> 00:25:33.970
PETE LEPAGE: I think one of the
things that really excites

00:25:33.970 --> 00:25:37.510
me with the web is, it's
not always about--

00:25:37.510 --> 00:25:39.690
the technology is not supposed
to used this way.

00:25:39.690 --> 00:25:45.450
It's that as browser vendors, or
as the people who make the

00:25:45.450 --> 00:25:50.070
specifications develop stuff,
they say, hey, we think it's

00:25:50.070 --> 00:25:51.310
going to get used this way.

00:25:51.310 --> 00:25:55.180
But then creative, brilliant
people like you guys come in

00:25:55.180 --> 00:26:00.030
and say, oh, hey, if I
do this and this, I

00:26:00.030 --> 00:26:01.840
can get this to happen.

00:26:01.840 --> 00:26:05.530
And suddenly you get something
that's never really been seen

00:26:05.530 --> 00:26:07.630
or done before.

00:26:07.630 --> 00:26:09.690
NICOLE MCDONALD: Yeah, it's
like using a hammer for

00:26:09.690 --> 00:26:11.495
something else other
than nailing.

00:26:14.600 --> 00:26:17.520
If there's a tool available,
then it can kind of push us

00:26:17.520 --> 00:26:22.150
into ways that we don't
reveal yet.

00:26:22.150 --> 00:26:25.100
GILLIAN FERRABEE: One other
thing that comes to mind from

00:26:25.100 --> 00:26:25.840
a live [? performance ?]

00:26:25.840 --> 00:26:30.230
point of view is there is a
different kind of intimacy.

00:26:30.230 --> 00:26:32.990
As Nicole was saying, you can
move the camera into places

00:26:32.990 --> 00:26:36.250
that you can't always
see from your seat.

00:26:36.250 --> 00:26:40.730
And then the other thing that's
way out there is the

00:26:40.730 --> 00:26:44.040
web provides a different kind
of live, which is--

00:26:44.040 --> 00:26:46.580
for instance, in the way that
if you're using an app,

00:26:46.580 --> 00:26:50.250
sometimes you can see who else
is using it at that moment.

00:26:50.250 --> 00:26:54.250
There's a collective
participation over time and

00:26:54.250 --> 00:26:59.130
space that you never have with
the limitations of 1,200

00:26:59.130 --> 00:27:02.920
people from 8:00 to 10:30 or any
form of live experience.

00:27:02.920 --> 00:27:07.600
There's that potential for
a different kind of live.

00:27:07.600 --> 00:27:09.950
NICOLE MCDONALD: And a very
new and exciting unity.

00:27:12.980 --> 00:27:17.100
There's people that are coming
together that would never have

00:27:17.100 --> 00:27:19.930
the opportunity to
come together.

00:27:19.930 --> 00:27:22.560
It's incredibly exciting.

00:27:22.560 --> 00:27:23.380
PETE LEPAGE: Cool.

00:27:23.380 --> 00:27:27.370
Well, let's talk about the
workflow, a little bit, of

00:27:27.370 --> 00:27:31.330
taking some of the actual
practical things and putting

00:27:31.330 --> 00:27:35.150
them onto the web into some
of those experiences.

00:27:35.150 --> 00:27:37.820
So Nicole, as you started going
through and saying, OK,

00:27:37.820 --> 00:27:42.690
this is what I want some of
these scenes to look like, how

00:27:42.690 --> 00:27:44.040
did you say--

00:27:44.040 --> 00:27:46.830
for example, the tree
of life scene--

00:27:46.830 --> 00:27:50.040
how did you translate that from
being something in your

00:27:50.040 --> 00:27:55.310
head to being something very,
like, touch, like, I can go

00:27:55.310 --> 00:27:56.575
and see that, I can
move around?

00:27:59.340 --> 00:28:02.580
NICOLE MCDONALD: I think it's
that this is about sketching.

